  "method": "We propose a single template—Intermediate Computation Traces (ICT)—that equips non-language models with an explicit, verifiable scratchpad they generate and consume before committing to a final prediction or action. ICT has three shared components: (1) a Step Generator that proposes a short sequence of intermediate states (e.g., visual evidence selections, subgoals, or intent facets) and associated actions (e.g., retrieve a patch, pick a skill, fetch items); (2) a Grounder–Retriever that executes each action to attach concrete evidence to the trace (segments/patch captions, one-step skill rollouts or success estimates, multi-view item candidates); and (3) a Faithfulness Evaluator that checks trace–evidence consistency with domain-executable tests and uses the score both as training signal and as a gating/halting mechanism. Training proceeds in two phases: supervised trace induction using teacher trajectories synthesized from strong heuristics or pretrained tools, then reinforcement-style fine-tuning that rewards both task success and faithful, useful traces. Like interleaved reasoning–retrieval in RAG for LLMs, the Step Generator alternates propose–execute–revise until a cap or a halting predicate is met, and the final solver conditions on the validated trace.",
  "rationale": "Intermediate computation helps when the raw mapping from inputs to outputs is either long-horizon (RL), compositional and cross-modal (vision), or multi-aspect with coverage/diversity requirements (recommendation). By forcing models to externalize and then verify partial computations, ICT reduces search depth, improves credit assignment, and provides alignment hooks that correlate with end-task accuracy. The seeds demonstrate that (i) interleaving reasoning with retrieval stabilizes exploration and improves performance, (ii) explicit, grounded intermediates (segments, scene-graph facts) and executable checks raise faithfulness and accuracy in VQA, (iii) subgoal images/plans and look-ahead skill models shorten RL horizons, and (iv) multi-view item representations and listwise feedback let recommenders reason over intents rather than a single undifferentiated score.",
