  "method": "We propose a Generalized Intermediate Computation (G-IC) framework that mirrors chain-of-thought with three shared modules across domains: (1) an Evidence Generator that produces compact, human-interpretable intermediate artifacts aligned to the task (e.g., per-frame captions, subgoal graphs, or intent sketches); (2) a Selector/Refiner that prunes or iteratively improves these artifacts before the final decision; and (3) a Decision Head that conditions on the verified intermediate evidence to output predictions, actions, or rankings. A lightweight Confidence Gate determines how many refinement steps to run per example, escalating computation on hard cases. Training is two-stage: first teach the Evidence Generator using weak or proxy supervision; then teach the Decision Head to rely on the evidence via supervised fine-tuning or imitation, with online refinement during rollouts or ranking.\n\nFor vision, the Evidence Generator is a small LVLM that produces progress-aware, per-frame captions and/or a compact scene/temporal graph. A tiny LLM selects question-relevant “core” frames and composes a concise evidence chain (e.g., object states changing over time). The Decision Head (a larger LVLM or task-specific vision model) consumes only the selected frames plus the evidence to reason and answer. We train this in two steps: first supervise per-frame progress captions and temporal key events; then train the reasoner to cite evidence and answer. At inference, the Confidence Gate uses a learned uncertainty head to decide whether to stop after selection or to generate additional evidence/refinement passes on ambiguous clips.\n\nFor reinforcement learning, the Evidence Generator builds a small belief/subgoal graph at each timestep: candidate waypoints or latent subgoals, predicted reachability and value deltas, and a compact belief state from a lightweight Bayesian network. A pseudo-interactive demonstrator labels the best next subgoal during rollouts (DAgger-style), yielding intermediate supervision without dense rewards. The Decision Head is the policy conditioned on the current observation and the subgoal/evidence chain; it executes short-horizon actions toward the selected subgoal, then replans, thereby converting long-horizon tasks into verified intermediate hops. We pretrain with behavior cloning and auxiliary prediction, then fine-tune with interactive data aggregation while maintaining the BN’s fast, sampling-based gradient updates to keep the intermediate beliefs cheap to learn and update online.\n\nFor recommendation, the Evidence Generator converts each session into a directed session graph augmented with a user-global attribute that summarizes long-term preference. It produces an explicit intent sketch: a topical mixture over item attributes, short-term transition motifs centered on the last interaction, and candidate next-item hubs from graph propagation. The Selector/Refiner restricts to a top-k candidate set and performs a few linear-time pairwise refinement passes that only compare adjacent items among the top-k, updating the ranking with each pass. The Decision Head scores candidates conditioned on the intent sketch and updated global attribute to produce the final list. The Confidence Gate stops early on confident sessions and triggers extra refinement passes or broader candidate exploration when uncertainty is high.\n\nAcross domains, the framework surfaces intermediate evidence that the final module must cite or condition on, improving robustness and sample efficiency and enabling adaptive compute. Because the evidence is structured (progress captions or keyframes in vision, subgoal graphs in RL, intent sketches in recommendation) and trained with targeted or pseudo labels, it remains stable under refinement and auditable at inference time.",
  "rationale": "LLM chain-of-thought works by externalizing latent reasoning into verifiable intermediate steps. G-IC brings the same pattern to non-language tasks by (i) defining domain-appropriate, compact evidence objects; (ii) training a small, specialized generator to produce them; (iii) letting a downstream head condition on and, when needed, refine these objects; and (iv) gating computation with uncertainty to spend more steps only when they matter. This preserves the benefits of decomposition and evidence citation while controlling cost.\n\nEach instantiation is grounded in mechanisms shown to help: progress-aware captions and core-frame selection provide textual and temporal scaffolds for video reasoning; pseudo-interactive subgoal supervision and a lightweight probabilistic belief support stable intermediate planning in sparse-reward RL; session graphs with a global attribute and efficient pairwise re-ranking create explicit, iteratively-refined intent sketches for recommendation. Uncertainty-aware gating makes the intermediate-computation budget adaptive, further improving accuracy-efficiency tradeoffs.",
