  "method": "We propose Verifiably Executed Intermediate Computation (VEIC): instead of latent chain-of-thought text, each model emits a compact, typed micro-program that is executed by a small, domain-specific runner to produce a trace of measurable predicates, counterfactual tests, and certificates before any final decision. A common Proposer–Executor–Auditor–Head pipeline is used across domains. The Proposer maps inputs to a domain-agnostic DSL with primitives (predicates, subgoals, swaps), constraints (pre/post-conditions, expected monotonic trends), and a budget (steps to execute). The Executor deterministically runs the program on a lightweight, differentiable simulator to return per-step test statistics and a state trajectory. The Auditor then stress-tests these claims with targeted perturbations and counterfactuals, aggregates evidence with an adaptive state estimator to form program-level confidence and certificates, and either approves or requests a revised program within budget. The Decision Head consumes only the executed-and-audited trace to output the answer, action, or ranking.\n\nVision (video QA/recognition). The Proposer outputs a temporal predicate program comprising a small set of structured hypotheses (e.g., appear(A), move_towards(A,B), contact(A,B), cause(A→B)) with expected progress signatures over time. The Executor builds per-object trajectories causally via a discretely-online CDE over detected tracks and regions, then compiles each hypothesis into differentiable tests driven by these continuous-time features, yielding per-frame truth-scores and a scalar progress curve. The Auditor mitigates self-evaluation bias by running paired counterfactual checks targeted at each hypothesis (e.g., frame-order reversal, entity label swaps, localized occlusion jitter) and rejects hypotheses whose truth-scores remain spuriously invariant. An adaptive Kalman-style update maintains a low-dimensional belief over hypothesis satisfaction as new frames arrive, using uncertainty-calibrated measurement noise from the predicate heads; the resulting certificate is a monotone-progress and falsification-pass flag plus a bounded variance on the final belief. The Decision Head answers using only certified hypotheses and their traces.\n\nReinforcement learning (sequential control). At each step, the Proposer emits an option program of 2–3 subgoals with pre/post-conditions and local cost budgets, along with a short rollout depth. The Executor evaluates options in a belief-aware simulator: a light Bayesian network maintains latent environment variables and task-relevant factors, and the policy/value dynamics are integrated with a discretely-online CDE to respect real-time causality. Option evaluation returns estimated value deltas and constraint violations from a handful of sampled rollouts without needing full posterior inference. The Auditor constructs a value-improvement certificate by aggregating the sampled deltas with an adaptive state update that explicitly tracks process/measurement noise; it also runs contrastive counterfactuals (e.g., swap post-conditions or scramble subgoal order) to detect overconfident plans. If the certificate meets a threshold (lower-bound on advantage with bounded variance), the option is executed; otherwise, the Proposer is prompted to refine subgoals within the remaining budget.\n\nRecommendation (session ranking). The Proposer emits an intent-sketch program over the current session: a small set of soft constraints (e.g., freshness, diversity, long-tail exploration) and K candidate pairwise swaps with predicted justifications. The Executor simulates counterfactual next-click likelihoods by running a session graph with a global user attribute forward and backward over the current slate; each candidate swap is scored by its certified regret reduction under the session dynamics. The Auditor prunes spurious justifications using deterministic uncertainty on the latent swap comparator and approves only swaps that pass a local robustness test (e.g., decoy-item insertion, neighbor-embedding jitter) and yield a positive certified gain. Instead of a fixed right-to-left schedule, swaps are selected by certificate strength until budget exhaustion, yielding a minimally edited slate accompanied by compact proofs of improvement.\n\nTraining and inference. VEIC is trained end-to-end with program-execution supervision signals: (i) program validity losses (pre/post-condition satisfaction), (ii) executor-aligned prediction losses (final task loss on audited traces), and (iii) auditor calibration losses (penalize certificates that disagree with held-out perturbation outcomes). Differentiation passes through executors via straight-through estimators for discrete program tokens and standard gradients for continuous runners; the Bayesian network parameters are updated with sampling-based gradients that avoid full inference. At inference, the system runs under a tight step budget (typically 3–6 executed statements), with early stopping if the auditor issues high-confidence certificates.",
  "rationale": "VEIC transfers the core benefit of chain-of-thought—structuring problems into intermediate steps—while making those steps executable and auditable rather than latent. By forcing hypotheses, subgoals, and swap justifications to run on small domain runners, the model exposes its reasoning to measurable tests and targeted counterfactuals, reducing the risk of self-reinforcing biases. A lightweight, adaptive state estimator integrates noisy step-wise measurements into compact certificates that gate final decisions, enabling accuracy gains without large compute overhead.\n\nThe approach is cross-domain yet concrete: in vision, temporal predicates verified against causal continuous-time features provide progress evidence more robust than free-form captions; in RL, short-horizon option programs evaluated under a belief-aware simulator produce value-improvement certificates that make exploration safer and more sample-efficient; in recommendation, certificate-guided minimal swaps turn intuitive intent sketches into verifiable local improvements. Uncertainty-aware auditing and adaptive evidence aggregation are the glue that makes these intermediate computations reliable at test time.",
